{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689901/1957112701/0329.xml":{"full_text":"Enter Into His Gates With Thanksgiving\nWednesday, November V, \\HI THI KEY WIST CITIZEN\nSpecial Services Set Thursday\nGrace Lutheran To\nMark Thanksgiving\nA special service of Thanksfiv\ning will be held at Grace Luther\nan Church, Flagler Avenue and\nTenth Street, on Thanksgiving\nDay. This service will begin at\n10 a: m. The pastor of Grace\nLutheran the Rev. Carl A. Sam-\nUnion Services\nWill Be Held\nTo Give Thanks\nSix churches of Key West will\nunite in Thanksgiving Service at\nFirst Methodist Church, Novem\nber 38 at 10 a. m.\nThe Rev. B. G. Henry, pastor\nof First Baptist Church, will de\nliver the sermon and the Rev.\nE. E. Snow, pastor of Old Stone\nChurch, will preside.\nParticipating churches will be:*\nFirst Baptist Church, the Rev.\nB. G. Henry, pastor; Glad Ti\ndings Tabernacle, the Rev. Wayne\nPitts, pastor; First Congregational\nChurch, Chaplain Bevan, pastor;\nFleming Street Methodist Church,\nthe Rev. C. H. Ketchum, pastor;\nSalvation Army, Captain and Mrs.\nHenry Russell; First Methodist\n\u201cOM Stone\u201d Church, Rev. E. E.\nSnow, pastor.\nThe offering will go for the work\nof the Salvation Army. First Meth\nodist will furnish music for the\nservice.\nFLORIDA ROOM\n\u2022949\u201c .\"S\u201d.\nApprox. 68c A Day\nand FLOOR \u2022SCREENED\n\u2022CYPRESS CEILING\n\u20224x4 UPRIGHTS \u00abDOUBLE\n2xB BEAMS \u00ab4x4 RAFTERS\nFinancing Available\nCall BALIDO\nCY MllB V A.M. 'W I P.M.\nUnion Thanksgiving Service\nThursday-10:00 A.M.\nFIRST METHODIST\n\"The Old Stone Church\"\nCORNER EATON AND SIMONTON STREETS\nSermon\nREV. B. G. HENRY\nPASTOR, FIRST BAPTIST CHURCH\nPARTICIPATING CHURCHES\nFIRST CONGREGATION CHURCH\nFIRST BAPTIST CHURCH\nGLAD TIDINGS TABERNACLE\nSALVATION ARMY\nFLEMING STREET METHODIST\nFIRST METHODIST\nWatch for Announcement of\nCHRISTMASTIDE SERVICES\nat Firet Methodirt \u201cOld Stone\u2019\u2019 Church\nSpecial\nTHANKSGIVING SERVICE\nPresbyterian Church of the Rock\nI*lB FLAGLIR AVINUI\n10 A.M., Thursday, November 28th\nample parking space\nSurgery For Children\nmetinger, will preach the sermon\non the subject: \u201cReceive Your\nDaily Bread With Thanksgiving\"\nThrough a special letter st in*\nvitation to the members and\nfriends of Grace Lutheran, the\npastor pointed out that it should\nbe very easy for us to give thanks\nto God. He said, \u201cHe is so good\nto us, even though we do not\ndeserve His goodness.\n\u201cIn the realm of nature God\ngives us more than enough. Few\nAmericans really know what it\nmeans to be hungry. We have an\nabundance of grain milk pro\nducts, and meat. While two-thirds\nof the world population is under\nnourished, we grapple with the\nproblem of surplus.\n\u201cWe also have countless social\nbenefits,\u201d the pastor continued,\n\u201cWe have freedom as it is found\nnowhere else in the world. In this\natmosphere of freedom family life\nblooms, education thrives, and bus\niness prospers. We are free to\nlive and love, free to learn and\nearn.\n\u201cIn view of all this, must we\nnot put some spiritual seat into\nour Thanksgiving Day celebra\ntion. We have something to thank\nGod for. We can\u2019t take this\nholiday on the run.\n\u201cMany people are thankful and\ngrateful every day,\u201d said Mr.\nSammetinger. \u201cMany thank God\neach day for His blessings. Yet\nif the spirit of Thanksgiving Day\nis to be preserved, Christiana mutt\nset a good example. The place\nof aU Christians or thia national\nholiday is in God\u2019s House to wor\nship and praise the Creator and\nRedeemer,\u201d the miwtotsr conclud\ned.\nTo show thanks to Ged Mt only\nwith the lips but also with the\nhands the members and Moods\nof Grace Luther an Church have\nbeen asked to otter unto the\nLord gifts of clothing and money.\nThe ladies of the congregation\nwill wrap the clothing and ship\nit to Lutheran World- RoMof to\nbe used by the needy in aU parts\nof the world.\nGrace Lutheran Church invites\nthe people of the community to\njoin in this service of praise and\nthanksgiving to the almighty God\nfor His rich Messings of the past\nA giant among rockets to the\nNavy\u2019s Viking, which has soared as\nhigh as 158 miles.\nPage 5\nEucharists Mark\nThanksgiving\nSt. Paul's Episcopal Church\nwill mark Thanksgiving Day\nwith two Eucharists at 7:30\nand 0:30 a. m. At tha latter\nchoral service the Rector, the\nRev- Whitney Church, will\npreach an the Thanksgiving\ntheme. Visitors are Invited to\nattend.\nOn Saturday, St. Andrew's\nDay, the 7:30 a. m. Eucharist\nwill ho a Corporate Cemmun\nion of the Brotherhood of St.\nAndrew and the men of the\nParish.\nBi-Lingual\nServices\nTo Be Held\nSpecial services at Latin Ameri\ncan Baptist Temple will be held\nThursday night at 7 p. m. Not\nonly does this date mark the fourth\nanniversary of the church but\nalso it marks the day for spec\nial Thanksgiving unto the Lord.\nThe pastors, The Rev. Ismael\nNegrin and Brother Morris Wright\nask that people take time on this\nspecial day to come with us for\nspecial worship service. There\nwill be special music as Brother\nHulquist, a gifted singer, will use\nhis talent for the Lord and raise\nhis voice in Thanksgiving in song.\nThe sermon in form of testi\nmony will be translated into Span\nish and the same congregation\nwiU hear both English and Span\nish. The hymns will be sung in\ntwo languages at the same time.\nThis being a bi-hngual church\ntwo services will be carried on at\nthe same time. English and Span\nish will be spoken.\nOne of the important factors\nof the service is to hear a man\nwho ran from God who now is\nrunning with God.\nThe ministers say he is here\nto tell how the Lord rescued him\nand brought him back to the know\nledge of Christ and into full time\nservice for the Lord.\nAfter the service a fellowship\nmeeting is to be held and refresh\nments wiU be served. Worship at\n7 p. m. on Thursday night.\nDram, Bugle\nCorps To Have\nBusy Holiday\nThe junior drum and bugle corp\nsponsored by the city recreation\ndepartment and directed by the\nRev. S. Kenneth Johnson is look\ning toward to a busy holiday week,\nend.\nThe corps will take part in a\nprocession Thanksgiving morning\nwhieh will march from Bayview\nPark at 9:30 a. m. to the Neigh\nborhood Thanksgiving Day ser\nvice at tiie First Presbyterian\nChurch.\nFriday morning, November 29,\nappradmataly SO boys and girls\nwill go to Marathon at the in\nvitation of the Marathon Ameri\ncan Legion Post to take part in\nexhibition drills with the Mara\nthon Drum and Bugle Corps, af\nter which they will be treated to\na picnic dinner.\nFriday evening the same group\nwill appear in the Conch Bowl\npre-game parade in downtown Key\nWest, and will later attend the\nfootball game as the guests of the\nLion\u2019s Club.\nPaul Albury reports that 75 have\nregistered for the Drum and Bu\ngle Corps; and an overwhelm\ning total of 114 girls have signed\nwith Mrs. J. R. Franklin for the\nbaton twirling class.\nThe Navy\u2019s second atom sub\nmarine. Seawolf, can circle the\nworld three times without refuel*\ning.\nMarines Will Stand Guard\nAt Presbyterian Services\nA squad of Marines will be\nstanding on guard Thanksgiving\nmorning in front of the First Pres\nbyterian Church where a Neigh\nborhood Thanksgiving Day service\nwill be held at 10 a. m.\nSgt. E. D. Pitman, Sgt. E. J.\nBush, Pfc. R. O. Southern, Pfc.\nW. G. Sizemore, Pvt. D. H. Hill,\nCpl. D. Little, and Cpl. W. J.\nWarner from the Marine Corps\nBarracks at Key West Naval Sta\ntion bearing ML rifles, will escort\nthe procession of scouts. choir\nmembers, veterans, and other units\nrepresentative of our communi\nty life to the church at the cor\nner of White and Washington\nStreets where they will take up\npositions at the entrance of the\nchurch.\nThese armed men will remind\nus by their presence that we wor.\nship God according to the dic\ntates of our own conscience, and\nenjoy the other Freedoms asso\nciated with American way of life\nonly because we have such men\nChristian Science\nSociety To Hold\nRites Thursday\nA special Thanksgiving service\nis announced by Christian Science\nSociety of Key West for 11 a. m.\non Thanksgiving Day. The ser\nvice will be held in the Church\nBuilding at 327 Elizabeth Street.\nOped to the public, the service\nwill include voluntary testimon\nies of gratitude by Christian Sci\nentists for God\u2019s goodness as shown\nin spiritual growth, physical heal\nings, and other blessings.\nA Lesson-Sermon for the day\nentitled \u201cThanksgiving\u201d will be\nread in all Christian Science\nchurches. Consisting of selections\nfrom the Bible and from the Chris\ntian Science textbook, \u201cScience\nand Health with Key to the Scrip\ntures\u201d by Mary Baker Eddy, the\nLesson-Sermon will emphasize the\nimportance of expressing gratitude\nto God in deeds as well as in\nspeech.\nThe service is open to the gen\neral public and local church mem\nbers have invited everyone to at\ntend.\nThat Really Was\nDaddy At Window\nEFFINGHAM, 18. LP\u2014Who was\nthe two-year-old boy and why did\nhe shout \u201cDaddy\u201d every time he\nwas taken to a studio window?\nThe double mystery confronted\nradio station WCRA yesterday.\nThe station broadcast a descrip\ntion of the tot, who was crying\nand without a coat or hat when\nfound wandering near the studio.\nClaudine Rush, the station\u2019s\nbookkeeper, noticed in trying tn\ncalm the boy that he cried except\nwhen she took him to the window.\nMrs. Ransom Wiedner, rec\nognizing the broadcast description\nof her son, soon arrived at the\nstation.\nThen she cleared up the rest of\nthe mystery by going to the win\ndow. Her husband was installing\na transformer on a utility pole\n\u2022cross the street.\nI WAS MARRIED IN\nFIRST METHODIST\n\"Old Slone Church\"\nSince the present Minister came Ie Key West six months\na\u00abo, many have said proudly to him, \"Wo wore married in the\nFirst Methodist \"Old Stone\" Church.** Our Present Sanctuary\nwas befun In 1177 and completed in 1873. Since 1782, 1,2*8\ncouples have boon married In the Church. This doos not In\nclude many married in the Church by visiting Ministers and\nChaplains.\nAt 5:00 P.M; Sunday, December 22, 1957\nA Special Christmas Service\nwill be held tor those married in the Church, still living, and\nin Koy West. If you wore married in the Old Stone Church\nand are still living in Key West, the Minister will appreciate\nyou filling bi the blank below and mailing It It him:\nMAIL TO: RiV. f. I. SNOW\nP.O. BOX **7\nKIY WIST, FLORIDA\nNAMI\naddrkss\nOATI OF MARRIAM\nstanding guard in many outposts\naround the world.\nA similar detail of veterans from\nArthur Sawyer Post of the Amer\nican Legion will serve to remind\nus of the patriotic sacrifices of\ncitizens for the preservation of\nour heritage and ideals from the\nfounding of our Nation.\nAdmiral F. D. McCorkle, Super,\ninteodent of Schools Horace O'-\nBryant, Judge Thomas S. Caro,\nand Chamber of Commerce Presi.\ndent Merville Rosam will speak\non the theme \u201cThank God For\nthe Indomitable American Spirit.\u201d\nThe public is invited to attend\nthis service. It is not expected\nthat all who come will be able\nto get into the building.\nProvision is being made for over\nflow seating on the patios; and\nan adequate public address sys\ntem. All who come are urged to\nbring canned goods and staple\ngroceries for presentation to the\nSalvation Army for distribution\nto the needy of the community\nbetween Thanksgiving and Christ\nmas.\nUshers will direct you to large\ncardboard boxes which will serve\nas collection points for this dona\ntion.\nKnow Your\nMailman\nJACK R. WILLIAMS\nnative Key Wester.\nJack R. Williams, 43, a native\nKey Wester is another of the local\nPost Office Department\u2019s staff of\nfloaters, or mailmen whose re\ngular duty is to fill in as auxi\nliary carriers when other mad\nmen are absent.\nWilliams and his wife Ottilee\nlive at 907 Ashe Street. They have\ntwo children, Don 24, and Jae\nqueline, 15.\nHe has been in the postal ser\nvice since January 1951.\nLike many other of the car\nriers, especially those born in\nKey West, Williams\u2019s hobby is\nfishing.\nCasts Get Glamorous\nCAMDEN, N.J. U*-Mrs. Jane\nBorn, director of nurses at Wet\nJersey Hospital here, is a lady\nwho thinks a little glamor may\nbe good for broken bones. Now\npatient* may order their plaster\ncasts in pink, yellow or blue, in\nstead of the old-fashioned white.\nReligious Services Are Integral Part Of Holiday\nAmericans Will Give Thanks,\nPray For President Tomorrow\nBy THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nAmericans prepared today to\ngive thanks for still another year\u2019s\nharvest of freedom and abun\ndance, but the shadow of Presi\ndent Eisenhower\u2019s illness dark\nened somewhat the usual joyful\nspirit of the time.\nPrayers for the President\u2019s\nswift and complete recovery will\nbe said tomorrow in many morn\ning religious services which have\nbeen an integral part of Thanks\ngiving ever since the Pilgrims\nfirst celebrated it.\nOtherwise, \u2019\u2022eports from across\nthe country indicated that Amer\nicans wiU follow the patterns set\nin past years.\nThey wAI rush from city to coun\ntry, from country to city, and\nfrom village to village, jamming\ntrains, planes, buses and private\ncars to join friends and relatives\nfor the day. Some will make it a\nfour-day weekend. To accommo\ndate all, railroads, airlines and\nbus companies are scheduling ex\ntra facilities.\nOne of the most unusual church\nservices tomorrow wiU be held in\nthe DeWitt Church, in an unheat\ned, as yet unfurnished building of\nth* Bernard Baruch bousing proj\nect in Manhattan\u2019s lower East\nSide. NondenomfoationM services\nwill be held in English, Spanish\nand Russian at the church, the\nfirst built inside a public housing\nproject in the city.\nYoungsters See\nTeacher Married\nOn TV Program\nDALLAS Television was al\nmost a school-wide activity at the\nJefferson Davis school yesterday.\nOne of the teachers, Marvin L.\nGrantham, was married on the\nBride and Groom show.\nSixteen TV sets were set up in\nclassrooms.\nNo one looked away from the\nset in Grantham\u2019s fifth grade\nclass. \u201cWasn\u2019t it beautiful?\u201d\nsighed one little girl as the music\nfaded.\nA deep red blush crept up the\ncheeks of a boy when the groom\nkissed the bride, the former Mise\nVerda Giles, a student in the Bay\nlor University school of nursing.\nPrincipal John J. Santillo said\nthere was no campaign to have\nthe youngsters bring the televi\nsion sets to school. \u201cThey aU vol\nunteered,\u201d he said.\nScudder Won\u2019t Run\nSANTA ROSA. Calif. \u00dcB-Rep.\nHubert B. Scudder (R-Calif.), says\nhe will not seek reelection from\nthe First California District.\nIn a farewell message yester\nday, the \u00ab9-year-old solon, who is\nserving his fourth term, saM \"I\nam looking forward to the time\nwhen the crowded day might be\nmore leisurely spent.\u201d\nMftapfefiivine\nV America** prayer* of thank* today\nare or the Providence that\n,n short 300 from\nthe pilgrims' struggle for existence\nto the mightiest nation in history...\nA H\nw are\nj<4 W Thankful that the opportunities for\ngreat accomplishment are today ae\n'widespread and unlimited\n,W eW \u2022reateet thank* is for the opportunity to freely\nworship God; to witness for Hi* Son our Savior J\nLey Memorial Methodist Church\nCORNER TRUMAN AND GIORGIA ST., AT BAYVIEW PARK\nCordially Invitee You and Your Family To\nThanksgiving Worthip Tomorrow Morning\nTIME: 10d0 O'CLOCK\nSERMON TOPIC: \"We Count Our Blessings\nSpecial Music by Junior Choir and Sanctuary Choir\n(NURSERY PROVIDED FOR INFANTS))\n-JAMES W. BUTCH, PaMor.\nTn Plymouth, Mass., the May\nflower ll\u2014-replica of the original\nP grim ship\u2014will be turned ever\ntoday to the Plymouth Plantation\nin colorful, costumed ceremonies\nTomorrow, there wM be a town\nwide open bouse, with costumed\nattendants playing host at such\nspots as Pilgrim Hall, the first\nchurch. Sparrow House and the\nold fort. In the afternoon, there\nwill be the traditional Pilgrim\nJT. PAUL'S\nEPISCOPAL CHURCH\nCORNER DUVAL AND EATON STREETS\nThe Rav'd Whitnoy Church, Rector\nThanksgiving Day\n7:30 and 9:30 A.M. (SUNG)\nFRIDAY and SATURDAY _\n7:30 A.M.\nVisitors Cordially Welcome at All Services\nDando Gracias\nA Dios\nPor\nPIEDAD STONE\nHoy incline mi fronte y debie mis rodillos\nAnte ese Dios viviente quo os Jesus mi Senor\nPara darle las gracias, en mi oradon canaille\nComo agradocimiento por su infinite amor.\nAl Dios quo me da fuerxas cuando voy entre espinaa\nY florecen las roses por su bonded y amor\nPues cuando las tiniebla me cubren, me ilumina\nY me dice, ono femes yo soy tu buen pastor.\nNo to abandono nunca y si es tu eruz pesada\nTo ayudaro a cargarla con todo el corazon\nVenid a mi los tristes con las almas cansadas\nQuo yo os dare el consuelo, la osperanza, el pardon\nComo lluvias do grade a mandada a ml vlda\nVendiciones del cielo por su divino amor\nY por su grade misma, voy ligada a su vida\nGracias, mil veces gracias, gracias to doy Sefiof. j\nI\nprocession by costumed townspeo\nple marching from Plymouth\nRock to church.\nTrailers Towed\nAcross the Street or\nAcross the Nation CALL\nMorgen Drive Awey. Inc.\nCY Mm","height":"26268","width":"19644"}}
